ere are ringside-seat arguments between people who don’t often get to engage with one another: right-leaning liberals like Peter Berkowitz and John Patrick Diggins, and leftier liberals like Michael Tomasky and Mona Harrington. The result is a lively and stimulating collection that articulates a clear-minded alternative to the conservative ascendancy in American history and offers a timely and essential contribution to the growing national debate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aLiberalismzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a20th century american radicals.  aamerica political philosophy.  aamerican enlightenment.  aamerican history.  aamerican liberalism.  aamerican politics.  acivic.  acivil rights era.  aclassical liberalism.  acold war.  ademocracy.  adiplomacy.  afamily and religion.  ajohn patrick diggins.  aliberal.  aliberalism and american values.  aliberalism in iran.  aliberalism.  amichael tomasky.  amona harrington.  anational debate.  anew liberalism.  apeter berkowitz.  apolitical ideology.  apostmodernism.  apostmodernity.  atolerance.1 aBerkowitz, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrinkley, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiggins, John Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDionne Jr., E. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrington, Mona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJumonville, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJumonville, Neil, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKazin, Mich